            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Fremont to Iranian immigrants, Kian Rashidi\u2019s childhood was a blend of two worlds. His father, a pragmatic software engineer, preached the virtues of a stable career, while his mother, who had a passion for Persian miniature painting, quietly nurtured Kian\u2019s artistic sensibilities. This duality defined his early life; he was the dutiful son who excelled in math but spent his evenings sketching floor plans for imaginary museums. Instead of a traditional STEM path, he found a compromise in exhibition design, a field that married his love for art with his innate need for structure and logic.\n\nHis move to San Francisco to pursue a Master of Fine Arts at California College of the Arts was a declaration of independence. He thrived in the program, mastering the art of storytelling through space and light. Upon graduating, however, the financial reality of the city set in. Faced with student debt, he made a pivotal choice: he accepted a lucrative offer as a Visual Merchandising Manager for a luxury apparel brand in Union Square, putting his dream of curating museum exhibits on hold.\n\nNow 29, Kian\u2019s life is a well-managed display. He lives in a meticulously organized Hayes Valley apartment, his commute a short MUNI ride away. His days are a blur of managing a team, approving layouts, and ensuring every mannequin and spotlight tells a compelling, commercial story. While he finds satisfaction in a perfectly executed window display, he often feels like his creativity is in a gilded cage, serving commerce instead of culture. His social circle is a mix of friends from CCA, with whom he discusses art theory over drinks, and work colleagues, who talk sales targets. A recent, amicable breakup has left him feeling adrift, prompting a re-evaluation of his long-term goals.\n\nKian\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deep but complicated. He loves the city's cultural pulse, spending weekends visiting small galleries in the Mission or volunteering at SFMOMA events. His dream of designing a major museum exhibition remains his animating force. He sees his current job not as a final destination, but as a strategic step\u2014a way to fund his future while honing his craft, waiting for the right moment to arrange the pieces of his own life into the exhibition he was always meant to create."
