            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was sixteen, sprawled on the living room rug in Fremont, sketching the floor plan for a fictional wing of the de Young. His father glanced over his shoulder and offered a pragmatic sigh. \u201cIt\u2019s a nice hobby, Kian, but it won\u2019t pay for a house.\u201d Later, his mother sat beside him, tracing the lines of his imagined gallery with her finger. \u201cThis is art, too,\u201d she whispered, her touch a quiet permission slip. In that moment, he understood his life would be a negotiation between two different definitions of value.\n\n2.\nHis first night in his Potrero Hill student apartment felt like a gasp of air after a lifetime underwater. The place was tiny, smelled of old paint and fog, and his few boxes seemed impossibly small. He didn't unpack or sketch. He just stood by the window, watching the distant lights of the city pulse. It wasn\u2019t loneliness he felt, but the immense, terrifying freedom of a blank canvas. For the first time, the space he had to design was entirely his own life.\n\n3.\nThe email with the job offer lit up his laptop screen in his cramped, post-grad apartment. The salary was a number so large it felt fictional, a stark contrast to the student loan balance glaring in another tab. He remembers the wave of profound relief washing over him, so strong it almost drowned out the quiet pang of regret. He accepted the offer and closed the browser tab for a museum internship application. It was the first time he consciously chose solvency over soul, promising himself it was temporary.\n\n4.\nHe remembers standing inside an installation at SFMOMA, a room sculpted entirely by colored light. It wasn't just visual; it was a physical space that told a non-verbal story, guiding emotion through form and hue. He felt a sharp, painful pang of professional jealousy and profound longing. It was a clear, perfect note of purpose cutting through the daily static of sales targets and profit margins\u2014a powerful reminder of the language he was meant to be speaking. This was his true north.\n\n5.\nA week after the breakup, he found himself obsessively re-aligning the books on his shelf in Hayes Valley. He stepped back, admiring the perfect gradient of color on the spines, and was struck by a hollow feeling. His apartment was pristine, curated, and silent. He\u2019d meticulously designed a beautiful life for one, only to realize he\u2019d left no room for the messy, unpredictable collaboration of another person. The perfect order he\u2019d built for comfort suddenly felt like the architecture of loneliness."
